      "type": "edit",
      "id": "a283256aec745d14",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "a283256aec745d14",
        "text": "You yourself used the method with your students during the shutdown. What was your experience?\nWe were \"caught\" by the shutdown during the current semester. Classroom courses had to be quickly converted to distance learning. Peripatetic courses were planned with a colleague. We wanted to work with the learning groups in the Bremgartenwald in Bern. Due to the shutdown, we were then no longer able to meet in person. We kept to the peripatetic format - but in compliance with the regulations on social distance. Students were given assignments to complete independently and on their own while walking around. Afterwards, there were opportunities for exchange on a digital learning platform. Many students reported back that it had been nice to work outside while walking, especially during the shutdown and the associated online study. During this time, many had to sit inside in front of the computer even more than usual. Overall, the feedback was very positive.\n\nMany teachers were teaching online for the first time because of Corona and had no time to prepare methodically. What adjustments are necessary when moving the classroom from the school building to the Internet - depending on the level?\nI believe that moving the classroom to the Internet cannot be done without some losses. Distance learning probably works well when learners and teachers have a sustainable relationship. And if there are certain technical prerequisites on both sides - stable Internet, competent handling of a digital learning platform. But my experience from online learning is that sometimes less is more. Especially with adult learners, it doesn't always have to be a live video conference. Books are still important learning media. And you can take them outside, too. Many learners have welcomed the flexible scheduling. A good balance between presence and independence is important.\n\nCould you imagine Corona leading to other changes in the school?\nDistance learning could bring the heterogeneity of family backgrounds, and therefore possibly inequality of opportunity, more into the open. Recent studies also show that children also suffered greatly psychologically from the shutdown and spent less time learning overall. Schools will likely need some time to tend to these wounds. The fear of a next shutdown could also lead to increased practice of self-organized learning in the future, even during periods of attendance. As a preventative measure, so to speak.\n\nDo you think the Swiss school system needs a fundamental modernization push in the wake of digitization?\nThere has been such a push as a result of the shutdown, but it has been implemented in different ways. But apart from digitization, it was at least as important during the shutdown to have a feel for the situation of learners, their resilience and ability to concentrate. I heard from students that they had to work harder than usual because of the many assignments during distance learning. Many have found the focus on the screen challenging. Teachers and learners alike have had to gain new experience in what the right dose and amount of material is. When I look at the students, I think that the teachers of tomorrow are already well-versed in digitalization and also have a variety of methods in their baggage.\n\nFor many years, frontal teaching was the be-all and end-all in school. Did those who were taught this way benefit less than students today who enjoy innovative teaching and learning methods that are in line with current research?\nEvery teaching format has strengths and weaknesses - including frontal teaching. Instructional formats are tied to overall societal trends. What was considered appropriate in the 1950s may not be appropriate in the 2020s - and vice versa. School is an experimental space that is shaped by everyone involved. Different teaching methods reinforce different competencies and bodies of knowledge. It's all about the mix."
